'''William Henry Conley''' (11 June 1840 &ndash; 25 July 1897), was a [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania|Pittsburgh]] philanthropist and businessman.<ref name=CMA19>''The Christian and Missionary Alliance'', Volume 19, Number 6, August 4, 1897, page 132</ref> He was married to Sarah Shaffer (1841-1908). Together, they provided organizational and financial support to religious institutions in the United States. Conley was co-owner of the Riter Conley Company, which provided steel and manufactured goods during the [[Second Industrial Revolution]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2009}}

==Support for religious groups==
===Home Mission===
The Conleys frequently held prayer meetings and events in their home ministry.<ref name=CMA19 /> Adventist minister [[George Stetson]] lived for a time with the Conleys during a prolonged period of illness until his death.<ref>Allegheny City census results of 1879 published in 1880</ref> The Conley home was sometimes kept open for weeks at a time in support of religious and charity efforts.<ref>The Christian Alliance and Foreign Missionary Weekly - Pittsburgh presidency April 13th 1894 Vol XII No. 15.</ref> J. H. Paton stated of the Conley home, "I have shared the generous hospitality of that Christian home. Often has the spacious parlor been opened for the purposes of praise and prayer, and for the proclamation of the good tidings. It has been to many a Bethel<U+2013>the house of God and the gate of heaven."<ref name=WHAug97>''The World's Hope'', August 1, 1897, pages 234-235</ref>{{Clarify|date=December 2009}}<!--Why is the particular wording of this quote important enough to include here? Sufficient to indicate that Conley frequently held prayer meetings. Clarify significance of quote or remove it.-->

===Zion's Watch Tower Tract Society===
William Henry Conley helped organize and provided funding for the formation of [[Watch Tower Bible and Tract Society of Pennsylvania|Zion's Watch Tower Tract Society]]. He was the first president of the Society from 1881 until 1884.<ref> "Legal Incorporation", ''Zion's Watch Tower,'' October 1884, p. 671 (reprint).</ref> The society later became the "Watch Tower Bible and Tract Society" of  [[Jehovah's Witnesses]].<ref name=proclaimers>''Jehovah's Witnesses: Proclaimers of God's Kingdom'' (Watchtower, 1993), p. 576.</ref>

===Christian and Missionary Alliance===
Conley was a member of the Board of Managers of the [[Christian and Missionary Alliance]] (CMA), and was instrumental in funding and organizing it at local, state and national levels through the International Missionary Alliance (IMA).<ref>''The Christian Alliance and Foreign Missionary Weekly'' - Pittsburgh presidency June 19th 1886 page 594</ref> In 1889, Conley funded and organized the CMA mission in Jerusalem under control of his home mission which would later come under the auspices of the IMA and eventually the CMA. <ref>''To see a promised land: Americans and the Holy Land in the nineteenth century'', Lester Irwin Vogel, page 115</ref> In the same year, the International Missionary Alliance was legally incorporated with W. H. Conleys $5000 contribution.<ref>To see a promised land: Americans and the Holy Land in the nineteenth century, Lester Irwin Vogel, page 115 </ref><ref>The Christian Alliance and Foreign Missionary Weekly March 21-28 1890 Vol IV No. 9-10. </ref><ref>''Twenty-five wonderful years, 1889-1914: a popular sketch of the Christian''<!--Is 'popular sketch of the Christian' part of the title, or a description of the content; if the latter, the description is POV-->, George Palmer Pardington 1914, page 208</ref> The Pittsburgh Branch of the Christian and Missionary Alliance was formally established in 1894. Conley was elected president of both the Pittsburgh branch and at the state level, an office which he retained until his death in 1897.<ref name=CMA19 />

==Business and charitable interests==
William Conley worked his way from bookkeeper to co-owner of the Riter Conley Company, a worldwide supplier to the drilling, mining, manufacturing, and marine industries.{{Citation needed|date=December 2009}} Conley was also Director and a stockholder of the Third National Bank of Allegheny.{{Citation needed|date=December 2009}}

William and his wife were active in several Pittsburgh charities, including<!--DO NOT restore redundant phrase "including but not limited to"--> an orphanage and school for children of African-American heritage, as well as a local hospital.{{Citation needed|date=December 2009}}

==Death==
William Henry Conley contracted [[influenza]] (indicated in one obituary as "[[La Grippe]]") early in 1897, from which he never fully recovered. His health was relatively stable until June, at which time he suffered a relapse, after which he seldom left his home. He became bedridden in the last week of his life; on the evening of July 25, 1897, his health rapidly declined, and he died at about 8:30pm. A funeral service was conducted at his home in Pittsburgh.<ref name=CMA19 /><ref name=WHAug97 />

William Conley was survived by his wife Sarah. After a period of prolonged illness, Sarah Conley died October 1, 1908.<ref name=WHAug97 /><ref>''Notes From the Home Field: Mr and Mrs. W. H. Conley: The Christian and Missionary Alliance'', November 21, 1908, page 131: "After a prolonged illness borne with hopefulness and courage, Sister Conley entered into rest October 1, leaving the whispered message behind&mdash;"It is all right.""</ref> In honor of her husband's memory, Mrs Conley left much of her estate&mdash;estimated at a value of nearly $500,000 (current equivalent, about ${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|.5|1908|r=2}}}} million)&mdash;to the Wylie Avenue Church and the Pittsburg Bible Institute.<ref name=CMA19 />

